<subSubSection lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1437,1286,1995]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,269,1646,1671]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Male:</emphasis>
Fastigium slightly wider than half width of scapus, narrowing apically, sometimes with parallel sides, slightly depressed and faintly sulcate dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[700,800,1682,1707]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 22. Dorsal view of pronotum. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (male); C, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (male); D, P. variicercis (male); E–F, P. salmani sp. n. (female); G, P. zonatus datca (male); I, P. variicercis (female); J–K, P. varicornis (male and female, not in scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242375/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 22J</figureCitation>
). Pronotum slightly selliform, with slightly constricted prozona, slighlly divergent posteriorwards on the metazona. Hind margin of metazona slightly concave (
<figureCitation box="[1318,1424,1718,1743]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 22. Dorsal view of pronotum. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (male); C, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (male); D, P. variicercis (male); E–F, P. salmani sp. n. (female); G, P. zonatus datca (male); I, P. variicercis (female); J–K, P. varicornis (male and female, not in scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242375/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Figs. 22J</figureCitation>
). Pronotum slightly concave dorsally (especially on the metazona) in profile (
<figureCitation box="[1001,1145,1754,1779]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[170,1424,202,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,193,1601]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 25. P. varicornis. A, D, male; B, E, female; C, pronotum of male in profile; F, male cerci from above; G, male cerci and subgenital plate; H, ovipositor (leg. R. Ebner in 1928 from Lebanon. Photos credit by Harald Bruckenr, Naturhistorisches Museum Wien, Austria)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242381/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 25 A–C</figureCitation>
). In profile, paranota with frontal margin perpendicular, caudal margin long and obtusely oblique (
<figureCitation box="[959,1062,1790,1815]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[170,1424,202,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,193,1601]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 25. P. varicornis. A, D, male; B, E, female; C, pronotum of male in profile; F, male cerci from above; G, male cerci and subgenital plate; H, ovipositor (leg. R. Ebner in 1928 from Lebanon. Photos credit by Harald Bruckenr, Naturhistorisches Museum Wien, Austria)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242381/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 25C</figureCitation>
). Tegmina shorter than pronotum with whitish edges and not reaching posterior margin of first tergite (
<figureCitation box="[937,1117,1826,1851]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[170,1424,202,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,193,1601]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 25. P. varicornis. A, D, male; B, E, female; C, pronotum of male in profile; F, male cerci from above; G, male cerci and subgenital plate; H, ovipositor (leg. R. Ebner in 1928 from Lebanon. Photos credit by Harald Bruckenr, Naturhistorisches Museum Wien, Austria)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242381/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Figs. 25K, 25D</figureCitation>
). Cerci gradually narrowing distalwards, distal 1/3–1/4 obtusely incurved; preapical rows 4–6 includes denticles (
<figureCitation box="[1102,1236,1862,1887]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[170,1424,202,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,193,1601]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 25. P. varicornis. A, D, male; B, E, female; C, pronotum of male in profile; F, male cerci from above; G, male cerci and subgenital plate; H, ovipositor (leg. R. Ebner in 1928 from Lebanon. Photos credit by Harald Bruckenr, Naturhistorisches Museum Wien, Austria)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242381/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 25F–G</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate small, slightly tapering backwards, with shallow incision on caudal margin (
<figureCitation box="[1005,1109,1898,1923]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[170,1424,202,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,193,1601]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 25. P. varicornis. A, D, male; B, E, female; C, pronotum of male in profile; F, male cerci from above; G, male cerci and subgenital plate; H, ovipositor (leg. R. Ebner in 1928 from Lebanon. Photos credit by Harald Bruckenr, Naturhistorisches Museum Wien, Austria)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242381/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 25G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
